article.headline: UC-Davis 45, Montana State 0
article.story: BOZEMAN, Mont. (AP) -- UC Davis capitalized on a strong passing game, third down conversions and turnovers in shutting out Montana State 45-0 Saturday. Jon Grant passed for 324 yards and five touchdowns and UC Davis outgained MSU 496 yards to 194 in handing the Bobcats their first shutout since a 44-0 loss at Portland State in 1997. It was the first home shutout since a 34-0 loss to Idaho in 1985. "We played well in all phases of the game," said UC Davis coach Bob Biggs. "In the second half, we rode the momentum." Tony Kays caught 10 passes for 143 yards and the first three TDs for the Aggies (2-1), ranked No. 21 in NCAA Division I-AA. No. 20 Montana State (1-2) managed just eight first downs -- one in the first half -- and Cory Carpenter was intercepted twice. The Bobcats converted just 4-of-14 first downs to 12-of-18 for the Aggies. "They have a veteran quarterback and a receiving corps that's not afraid of third down," said MSU coach Mike Kramer. "What was killing us was the throws down the field on third down." UC Davis scored twice in the final 2:11 of the first half. Emmanuel Benjamin kicked a 25-yard field goal, and after an interception by Nevan Bergan, Kays caught a 22-yard pass from Grant with 26 seconds left, giving the Aggies a 17-0 lead. "It was a tight game until we stopped and they kept going," Kramer said. "That touchdown that they got at the end of the first half just opened the floodgates." During the first drive of the second half, Montana State was penalized four times for a total of 25 yards and managed just four yards in total offense before having to punt. Five plays later, Grant hit Kays on a 21-yard TD pass, putting UC Davis up 24-0. MSU fumbled on its next possession. Jonathan Barsi recovered, and the Aggies needed just six plays to take a 31-0 lead on a 15-yard pass from Grant to Luke McDonough with 3:19 left in the third quarter. "We got them on their heels a little bit," Biggs said. "I just don't think they ever got in a rhythm." Mike Morales intercepted Carpenter on the next play, and Grant hit Marcus Nolan for a 25-yard TD pass, giving UC Davis a 38-0 lead with 2:20 left in the third. Backup quarterback Tim Plough hit Kale Turner on a 33-yard touchdown pass with 9:47 remaining for the final score. Alex Garfio rushed 10 times for 42 yards and caught two passes for 19 yards for Davis, while Plough passed for 69 yards. Carpenter completed 12-of-22 passes for 119 yards. Backup Jack Rolovich completed 5-of-13 passes for 73 yards, but had a punt blocked by Mike Healy and had to chase down the ball after the snap on another punt rolled between his legs. Bobcat receivers had three drops on their final drive. MSU free safety Ryan Force suffered a dislocated shoulder when tackling Grant as he dove for a touchdown with less than three minutes left in the first quarter. On the next play, Grant hit Kays for a 2-yard TD pass with 2:24 left in the first quarter. "In losing Ryan Force, we lost our communication," said Kramer, who also lamented his team's "totally ineffective running game." The Bobcats netted just 2 yards rushing. "Our offensive line is not playing very well right now," he said. The loss of Force brings to four the number of key Bobcat players on the injured list. Tight end Elliott Barnhart and running back Evin Groves are out, likely until October, with torn knee ligaments, and leading receiver Josh Lewis is expected to miss at least two games with a knee injury. "You've got to be able to run your offense and defense so the loss of one guy isn't tantamount to the mine shaft caving in," Kramer said. Montana State had allowed just 240 yards passing in its previous two games, but gave up 393 to the Aggies. The Bobcats could get no closer than 33 yards from the UC Davis end zone. Michael Jefferson caught two passes for minus 9 yards. It was the second loss for the Bobcats since their season-opening 19-10 upset of Colorado. "We lost a little bit of our foundation," Kramer said. "There's some huge issues that I've got to take care of" this week, said Kramer, who didn't allow his players to talk to the media after the game. "At no time have we gone into the Big Sky Conference coming off a 45-0 pasting."
